org.qbroker.common

Class StringKeyChain

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.qbroker.common.KeyChain
      • org.qbroker.common.StringKeyChain
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.util.Comparator

    public class StringKeyChain
extends KeyChain
    StringKeyChain contains an array of the sequence keys, timestamp, metadata and objects. The sequence key is stored in an array with the internal index to the object and timestamp. The data type of the sequence key is String. StringKeyChain has also the support for MetaData as an option so that extra information can be stored to a separate array together with each object. The metadata is an int array. StringKeyChain has a public method of sort(). It sorts the objects in the ascending order according to their sequence keys. The index of the keys may not be same as their internal index to the object.

    This is NOT MT-Safe. Therefore please use it with care.
    Author:
    yannanlu@yahoo.com

      • find

        public int find(java.lang.Object key)
        It looks for the given key in a sorted instance of KeyChain. If the key is found, the last index of the key will be returned. Otherwise, it returns a negative number. For a negative return value of r, the index of -(r+1) specifies the index at which the specified key can be inserted to maintain the sorted order.
        Specified by:

      • locate

        public int locate(long currentTime,
         int bakeTime)
        It assumes the key chain has been sorted in ascending order. Then it looks for the last fully baked key. Upon found the key, it returns the number of keys with lower values or same value as compared to the last fully baked key. Otherwise, it returns 0.
